"CORE_NARRATIVE: Real-world environments are dominated by non-Lambertian surfaces, yet traditional light field depth estimation remains fundamentally paralyzed by the Lambertian assumption, creating dangerous blind spots for autonomous systems. Rather than treating specular and scattered reflections as noise to be ignored, we translate these complex light-matter interactions into physical priors (via k-space frequency analysis) and explicit uncertainty signals (via flat cost volumes). By routing these physically-modeled uncertainty regions through neighborhood propagation, we break the traditional accuracy ceiling and enable robust light field depth estimation in complex, real-world scenes.\n\nINTRO_HOOK: Open by highlighting the paradox of modern light field cameras: despite their theoretical superiority in capturing directional light, their practical deployment in robotics and autonomous navigation is crippled because traditional EPI analysis assumes perfect Lambertian diffusion, causing catastrophic depth estimation failures on ubiquitous mirrors and glass. \n\nGAP_BRIDGE: Transition from related work by emphasizing that previous methods attempt to mathematically brute-force or smooth over non-Lambertian artifacts, completely missing the underlying physics. State that to cross this chasm, the field must shift from blind noise-filtering to explicit material classification, bridging electromagnetic theory (Maxwell to BRDF) with deep learning architecture design.\n\nMETHOD_JUSTIFY: Frame the network architecture not as an arbitrary choice, but as a physical necessity: the dual-mask and MRI-like k-space are required to mathematically decouple diffuse, specular, and scattered frequency signatures, while the GCD and SAM-guided energy optimization acts as a physical filter to isolate true depth from specular artifacts. The U-Net's use of flat cost volume responses must be justified as a deliberate, physics-informed trigger to abandon flawed EPI consistency and instead infer depth via trusted neighborhood propagation.\n\nEXPERIMENT_VALIDATE: Design the evaluation metrics and datasets specifically to punish the \"Lambertian ceiling,\" prioritizing quantitative and visual results on highly specular and transparent scenes. Experiments must explicitly demonstrate a high contrast in the NL/L (Non-Lambertian to Lambertian) energy ratio, proving that the model successfully decouples true depth from complex light-matter interactions where traditional EPI methods fail entirely.\n\nCONCLUSION_ECHO: Conclude by returning to the deployment bottleneck, stating that by translating physical light-matter interactions into frequency-domain features and cost-volume uncertainty, this work fundamentally resolves the blind spots that have historically restricted light field cameras to controlled, matte environments. \n\n***\n\n**Key Phrases to Embed in Each Section (Actionable Cheat Sheet):**\n*   **Introduction:** \"complex light-matter interactions\", \"violates view-consistency\", \"dangerous deployment blind spots\"\n*   **Gap/Bridge:** \"shift from mathematical smoothing to physical modeling\", \"explicit Lambertian vs. non-Lambertian classification\"\n*   **Method:** \"MRI-like k-space angular frequency\", \"frequency-domain signatures\", \"flat cost volumes as explicit uncertainty signals\"\n*   **Experiments:** \"breaking the Lambertian accuracy ceiling\", \"decoupling true depth from specular artifacts\", \"robustness on scattering/specular regions\"\n*   **Conclusion:** \"physical priors\", \"elevating light field deployment to real-world complexity\""